{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489431"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:16:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"658"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/658"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.11,0.07,0.6,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101426"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/658"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"658"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83864"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"498"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"4159"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9097"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44470"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101426"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old woman attends the Emergency Department with a two-day history of nausea, vomiting and constipation. She has not opened her bowels for five days or passed any flatus for two days and has started to have episodes of cramp-like abdominal pain. She has a medical history of Parkinson\u0027s disease and dyslipidaemia, with an appendicectomy 30 years ago. Her medications include simvastatin and aspirin. On examination she appears uncomfortable. Her vital signs are within normal limits and abdominal examination shows that the abdomen is distended, soft and with no areas of tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations would be most appropriate at this stage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastrografin follow-through","CT scan with oral contrast","Gastrografin enema","Erect plain abdominal X-ray","CT scan with oral and intravenous contrast"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient almost certainly has small bowel adhesive-obstruction. Adhesions are a common cause of small bowel obstruction and a previous appendicectomy (often decades earlier) is often the trigger. Today\u0027s management of such problems should first of all focus on the clinical picture and if some form of radiological investigation is considered, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eplain X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E will confirm the diagnosis and if further information is required, it should be a plain CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiving oral contrast\u003Cstrong\u003E (eg. CT scan with oral +/- IV contrast) \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be erroneous - as the patient may require prompt surgical intervention and oral contrast in an obstructed gut would increase the risk of aspiration. Whilst a plain abdominal radiograph would confirm the diagnosis of small bowel obstruction, a non-contrast CT scan would help define the site and extent of any adhesions. In addition, the CT scan might pick up other pathology that might be contributing to the patient\u0027s problem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the underlying problem is thought to be that of adhesive-obstruction, most cases will resolve with conservative treatment of gut rest and intravenous fluids. Should the obstruction not resolve then a \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrografin follow-through\u003C/strong\u003E can be therapeutic in refractory cases. Failure of progress of the gastrografin after 24 hours would suggest the need for surgical intervention. A \u003Cstrong\u003Egastrografin enema\u003C/strong\u003E is used occasionally in some cases of faecal impaction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A plain abdominal X-ray is a simple investigation to arrange when looking for abnormal gas patterns in cases of suspected obstruction."],"references":["Bax T, Macha M, Mayberry J. The utility of CT scan for the diagnostic evaluation of acute abdominal pain. Am J Surg 2019;217:959-66. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30824170/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83864"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"658"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83864"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-01T19:52:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-01T19:53:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"658"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101426"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-2